# Spring Boot Auto-Configuration Validation Rules

## Applicability

Apply this rule when changing:

- Spring Boot auto-configuration
- conditional bean registration
- `@ConfigurationProperties`
- optional dependency activation
- bean override behavior
- startup validation
- Actuator endpoints
- health indicators
- servlet or WebFlux auto-configuration
- auto-configuration imports and metadata

Before editing, inspect:

- the owning module
- existing conditions
- property metadata
- optional classpath assumptions
- current bean graph
- `ApplicationContextRunner` tests
- startup diagnostics
- affected runtime dependencies

## Ownership

Spring Boot auto-configuration owns:

- bean wiring
- typed startup properties
- conditional activation
- startup diagnostics
- Actuator integration
- translation from startup configuration into core contracts

It must not own:

- tracing algorithms
- control-protocol decoding
- domain validation
- sampling or scrubbing implementation
- runtime-state transitions
- JMX/OpenMBean transport logic
- application-facing API models

Core owns runtime behavior, policies, lifecycle, and safety invariants.

## Auto-Configuration Registration

Use:

- `@AutoConfiguration`
- `META-INF/spring/org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.AutoConfiguration.imports`

Do not add new legacy `spring.factories` registration unless a verified compatibility requirement explicitly requires it.

If `spring.factories` still contains another supported mechanism, do not delete it blindly.

Each auto-configuration class should own one coherent capability.

Avoid one large auto-configuration class that wires unrelated concerns.

## Conditional Bean Rules

Do not apply conditions mechanically.

Choose the condition that expresses the real contract.

### `@ConditionalOnClass`

Use when:

- an optional library is required
- an integration must back off when a type is absent
- servlet and WebFlux classpaths must remain isolated

### `@ConditionalOnMissingBean`

Use when:

- replacement is intentionally supported
- there is one clear fallback implementation
- replacement cannot bypass mandatory safety invariants

Do not use it for mandatory safety components.

### `@ConditionalOnProperty`

Use when:

- activation is explicitly configurable
- the default is documented
- disabled behavior is tested
- property semantics are unambiguous

Do not use permissive defaults for risky mutation or unsafe capabilities.

### Unconditional Beans

An unconditional bean is acceptable only when:

- the capability is mandatory
- required classes are always present
- no configurable back-off contract exists
- startup failure is preferable to silent absence

Do not register optional infrastructure unconditionally.

Do not rely on bean registration order as hidden control flow.

## Configuration Properties

Use:

- `@ConfigurationProperties`
- strongly typed fields
- explicit defaults
- validation
- immutable configuration where practical
- generated configuration metadata
- JavaDoc for public adoption properties

Avoid:

- scattered `@Value`
- direct `Environment` reads in ordinary components
- stringly typed booleans, enums, and numbers
- hidden fallback values
- duplicate property models
- mutable singleton configuration

Property objects describe desired startup configuration.

They do not automatically represent live runtime state after mutation.

## Property Validation

Fail startup when:

- a mandatory safety invariant is violated
- a required value cannot be interpreted safely
- mutually exclusive critical options are enabled
- an explicitly enabled mandatory integration is unusable

Back off or disable only the affected capability when:

- the integration is optional
- the missing dependency is expected
- tracing is explicitly disabled
- continuing is safe and documented

Do not silently fall back to permissive behavior.

Error messages must include:

- property or capability name
- invalid value category
- expected action
- whether startup is blocked or the capability is disabled

Do not expose secrets in validation errors.

## Safe Defaults

Defaults are product behavior.

Safe defaults include:

- runtime mutation disabled
- optional integrations disabled or absent when dependencies are missing
- no startup network calls
- no hidden global OTel mutation
- read-only diagnostics available only when safe
- invalid mandatory safety configuration fails clearly
- disabled capabilities create no unnecessary beans

Do not inherit framework defaults without reviewing their tracing and security impact.

## Bean Creation

Prefer:

- constructor injection
- immutable collaborators
- conditional creation for optional capabilities
- explicit lifecycle ownership
- lazy initialization for expensive optional integrations
- eager fail-fast initialization only for mandatory safety validation

Do not:

- create network clients during ordinary configuration-class execution
- perform runtime mutation during bean construction
- start unmanaged background threads
- register JMX side effects without lifecycle ownership
- write files
- mutate system properties
- access Docker
- block indefinitely

Do not mark every bean `@Lazy` mechanically.

## Optional Classpath

Optional integrations must back off cleanly.

Use:

- `ApplicationContextRunner`
- `FilteredClassLoader`
- focused classpath smoke tests

Verify:

- unrelated beans still start
- no `NoClassDefFoundError`
- optional types are not eagerly loaded
- condition reports are understandable
- servlet and WebFlux integrations remain isolated
- disabled capabilities create no unnecessary beans

Do not reference optional types in unconditional signatures or static initializers.

## Bean Override Policy

Classify each important bean as:

- platform-mandatory
- intentionally user-replaceable
- internal/test-only replaceable

For user-replaceable beans:

- document the contract
- use `@ConditionalOnMissingBean`
- test replacement
- preserve mandatory safety invariants

Do not expose internal runtime components as extension points merely because Spring allows bean replacement.

## Runtime Control

Runtime mutation is privileged.

Auto-configuration must ensure:

- mutation disabled by default
- enablement explicit
- startup diagnostics expose gate state
- validation-only requests do not apply
- read requests do not mutate
- rejected mutations preserve snapshot, version, source, and last-known-good state

Do not let bean replacement bypass the mutation gate.

Spring owns startup policy; core/runtime owns live state.

## Actuator and Health

Actuator endpoints are operational APIs.

They must:

- be read-only by default
- expose bounded safe state
- distinguish desired startup configuration from live applied state
- avoid secrets, PII, raw payloads, and implementation objects
- use explicit guards for mutation
- have a documented operator use case

Liveness must not depend on optional exporter or collector availability.

Readiness should include only dependencies required for correct service behavior.

Use diagnostics for detailed tracing state instead of overloading health.

## Diagnostics

Safe diagnostics may expose:

- tracing active or no-op
- runtime or agent mode
- active servlet/reactive adapters
- sampling mode
- mutation gate state
- applied policy version and status
- scrubbing rule summary or fingerprint
- exporter/processor readiness
- ignored or invalid configuration names
- actionable warnings

Do not expose:

- credentials
- raw control payloads
- raw PII
- full environment
- mutable live collections
- unbounded maps
- implementation object dumps

## Pre-Production Policy

The tracing solution is pre-production.

Breaking property, bean, package, and auto-configuration changes are allowed when they materially improve:

- ownership
- safety
- optional classpath isolation
- property taxonomy
- dependency graph
- diagnostics
- adoption simplicity

Prefer direct migration and deletion over:

- compatibility aliases
- duplicate bean names
- deprecated bridges
- dual property binding
- old/new auto-configuration paths

A breaking change must still update all repository consumers, metadata, docs, samples, Helm mappings, and tests.

Do not use pre-production status to justify arbitrary Spring churn.

## Testing

Use `ApplicationContextRunner` by default.

Test:

- default context
- enabled context
- disabled context
- invalid property
- missing optional class
- supported user override
- bean absence
- no eager initialization
- diagnostics
- configuration metadata where relevant

Use `@SpringBootTest` only when a complete application lifecycle, web stack, or Actuator interaction is required.

For risky properties, include negative tests.

## Architecture Fitness

Protect where practical:

- API has no Spring dependency
- core has no Spring dependency
- servlet and WebFlux remain isolated
- auto-configuration does not own domain validation
- JMX/OpenMBean types do not leak into API
- optional integrations do not load when absent
- runtime mutation remains disabled by default
- obsolete property aliases and bean names do not return
- legacy auto-configuration registration does not return without approval

Do not weaken architecture rules to make generated code compile.

## Verification

Run the narrowest affected tasks first:

```powershell
.\gradlew.bat :platform-tracing-spring-boot-autoconfigure:compileJava --no-daemon
.\gradlew.bat :platform-tracing-spring-boot-autoconfigure:test --no-daemon
```

Run servlet/reactive tests when those adapters change.

Run architecture, Javadoc, starter dependency smoke, full-build, or E2E gates when the changed boundary requires them.

## Required Report

A non-trivial auto-configuration change report must include:

```text
Capability:
Owner module:
Properties added, changed, or removed:
Default behavior:
Beans added, changed, or removed:
Conditions:
Override policy:
Optional classpath behavior:
Startup failure/back-off behavior:
Actuator/diagnostics:
Tests and E2E:
Architecture fitness:
Residual risks:
```

Use `PASS`, `PASS_WITH_WARNINGS`, `INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE`, or `FAIL` according to executed evidence.
